ce:section.ce:para:
In a first phase, the environmental impacts were analyzed and compared using a weight-based functional unit (FU) of 1 kg of produced material. As previously reported, using a weight or volume-based FU is useful to compare the manufacturing of an equivalent quantity of similar nanomaterials. (Feijoo et al., 2017; Hischier and Walser, 2012) The resulting impacts were normalized in a second phase by considering each photocatalysts' % ln (C) and k as function-based FUs. The former parameter measures the enhancement in photocatalytic activity over bare TiO2 by adding CDs and is calculated according to Eq. 1 (Table 2
                           ). The latter parameter corresponds to the rate constant of the photodegradation reaction of target organic pollutants, as catalyzed by the NCs (Table 3
                           ). In short, k is a proportionality constant that quantifies the rate and direction of a chemical reaction. These were chosen as FUs, as they are important indicators of the purpose for which the materials were made, thus accounting for the possibility that a higher functionality of the resulting material may justify a more resource and energy-intensive synthesis. Both function-based FUs were calculated by dividing the relevant property (% ln (C) or k) of the best-performing composite by those of the other composites. (Fernandes et al., 2020; Sendão et al., 2023a).
